1
00:00:02,530 --> 00:00:04,930
So I'm driving my car the other night,

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:06,930
and what do you think happens?

3
00:00:08,600 --> 00:00:11,800
I crashed into a utility pole.

4
00:00:11,860 --> 00:00:14,930
Then, to add insult to injury...

5
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:18,160
I was electrocuted.

6
00:00:18,230 --> 00:00:20,630
What can I say?

7
00:00:20,700 --> 00:00:23,930
It was one of those days.

8
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:26,930
All my neighbors heard it happen,

9
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:30,160
so they quickly left their microwaved burritos...

10
00:00:30,230 --> 00:00:34,700
and their expensive jars of moisturizer...

11
00:00:34,760 --> 00:00:39,460
and their racy pay-per-view movies...

12
00:00:39,530 --> 00:00:41,130
And they hurried outside,

13
00:00:41,200 --> 00:00:44,100
excited to see what all the ruckus was about.

14
00:00:44,160 --> 00:00:47,460
But then, when they saw it was me,

15
00:00:47,530 --> 00:00:50,430
this weird thing happened.

16
00:00:50,500 --> 00:00:55,500
For a moment, no one moved or said anything.

17
00:00:55,560 --> 00:00:57,860
They just stared.

18
00:00:57,930 --> 00:00:59,160
And then...

19
00:00:59,230 --> 00:01:00,800
Oh, my god.

20
00:01:00,860 --> 00:01:02,630
All hell broke loose.

21
00:01:02,700 --> 00:01:04,460
Does anybody know C.P.R.?

22
00:01:04,530 --> 00:01:05,900
There's been an accident.

23
00:01:05,960 --> 00:01:08,430
Edie!

24
00:01:08,500 --> 00:01:10,260
Can you hear me?

25
00:01:10,330 --> 00:01:13,830
Yes, everyone suddenly became very concerned,

26
00:01:13,900 --> 00:01:15,330
which was touching,

27
00:01:15,400 --> 00:01:18,630
but ultimately pointless.

28
00:01:20,200 --> 00:01:23,060
Moments before the ambulance finally arrived,

29
00:01:23,130 --> 00:01:25,600
I heard someone whisper...

30
00:01:25,660 --> 00:01:27,130
Don't worry, Edie.

31
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:30,100
You're gonna get through this. You're gonna be just fine.

32
00:01:30,160 --> 00:01:34,000
Susan Mayer... wrong again.

33
00:01:34,060 --> 00:01:37,430
Two seconds later, it happened.

34
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:40,260
With all of my neighbors surrounding me,

35
00:01:40,330 --> 00:01:43,200
I took my last breath.

36
00:01:43,260 --> 00:01:44,760
The good news?

37
00:01:44,830 --> 00:01:46,960
I died just like I lived...

38
00:01:47,030 --> 00:01:52,960
as the complete and utter center of attention.

39
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:07,330
Two days after I kicked the proverbial bucket,

40
00:02:07,400 --> 00:02:11,130
My husband asked my neighbors to do me a favor.

41
00:02:11,200 --> 00:02:13,530
You could tell from the looks on their faces

42
00:02:13,600 --> 00:02:18,200
it wasn't something they... wanted to do,

43
00:02:18,260 --> 00:02:21,600
But... They agreed to do it anyway.

44
00:02:21,660 --> 00:02:25,200
So the next day, they piled into a car

45
00:02:25,260 --> 00:02:27,930
with two thermoses filled with coffee,

46
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,500
a basket filled with baked goods

47
00:02:30,560 --> 00:02:35,100
and an urn that was filled with... me.

48
00:02:40,900 --> 00:02:43,630
I hate that we have to do this.

49
00:02:43,700 --> 00:02:47,430
So you've said.
I mean, it really is the kind of thing a relative should do.

50
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:50,860
Maybe it is, but we're in the car, on our way there,

51
00:02:50,930 --> 00:02:54,100
so stop your bitching.
Well, can you at least put the radio on?

52
00:02:54,160 --> 00:02:57,060
I won't feel like bitching if I can sing along to something.

53
00:02:57,130 --> 00:02:59,030
If you start singing, I'll start bitching,

54
00:02:59,100 --> 00:03:01,400
and you don't want that.
It's a 4-hour drive.

55
00:03:01,460 --> 00:03:03,760
We have to do something to pass the time.

56
00:03:03,830 --> 00:03:06,860
Here's a thought. Why don't we talk about Edie?

57
00:03:06,930 --> 00:03:08,730
And say what?

58
00:03:08,800 --> 00:03:11,730
I don't know, but she is the reason we're on this trip.

59
00:03:11,800 --> 00:03:14,130
Uh, maybe we could share memories or tell stories.

60
00:03:14,200 --> 00:03:16,730
Why don't you start with the time

61
00:03:16,800 --> 00:03:19,360
she tried to steal your comatose boyfriend?

62
00:03:19,430 --> 00:03:21,360
That was fun.
Okay, I was thinking

63
00:03:21,430 --> 00:03:23,830
of stories that put Edie in a positive light.

64
00:03:23,900 --> 00:03:27,200
And after that five minute is up, then what do we do?

65
00:03:27,260 --> 00:03:30,300
The woman is dead, people. Let's honor her memory.

66
00:03:30,360 --> 00:03:33,930
Well, I'm all for saying a few nice things...

67
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:36,300
But you were never really friends.

68
00:03:36,360 --> 00:03:39,460
You and Edie clashed right from the start.

69
00:03:39,530 --> 00:03:42,500
Yeah.

70
00:03:42,560 --> 00:03:45,900
That's what everybody thinks.

71
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:48,360
But the the first time we met,

72
00:03:48,430 --> 00:03:52,460
it seemed like we'd end up being the best of friends.

73
00:04:01,830 --> 00:04:03,930
Oh, that's disgusting.

74
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:06,000
No, it's okay.

75
00:04:06,060 --> 00:04:08,330
It landed on the detergent box.

76
00:04:08,400 --> 00:04:09,560
Here.

77
00:04:09,630 --> 00:04:11,000
You go buy yourself a fresh doughnut

78
00:04:11,060 --> 00:04:13,360
or booze, crack, whatever eases the pain.

79
00:04:13,430 --> 00:04:14,900
Just move it along.

80
00:04:15,660 --> 00:04:19,600
Uh, you think I'm homeless. Oh, no, no, no.

81
00:04:19,660 --> 00:04:21,200
No, I live here.

82
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:25,160
I... I can prove it.

83
00:04:25,230 --> 00:04:27,760
I know exactly what's in this garbage bag.

84
00:04:27,830 --> 00:04:30,600
Um, empty carton of eggs, coffee grinds,

85
00:04:30,660 --> 00:04:31,960
shampoo bottle...

86
00:04:32,030 --> 00:04:33,900
Wart removal cream?

87
00:04:35,830 --> 00:04:38,700
You're right. I'm homeless.

88
00:04:40,060 --> 00:04:43,500
Susan Mayer. Oh.

89
00:04:43,560 --> 00:04:46,330
It's all cleared up.

90
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:49,960
Mm. Edie Britt. I just moved in down the street.

91
00:04:50,030 --> 00:04:52,600
Oh, yeah. I saw the moving van. Welcome.

92
00:04:52,660 --> 00:04:54,130
Thanks.

93
00:04:54,200 --> 00:04:56,300
So is it just you, or do you have a family?

94
00:04:56,360 --> 00:04:58,730
I have a son. He lives with his dad.

95
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:01,800
It's a long story. I'll tell you one day over a margarita.

96
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:06,760
You wanna invite me in for a margarita?

97
00:05:06,830 --> 00:05:09,700
How about coffee? I just put on a pot.

98
00:05:09,760 --> 00:05:11,030
Great.

99
00:05:11,100 --> 00:05:13,500
You can fill me in on all of the neighborhood gossip,

100
00:05:13,560 --> 00:05:15,460
starting with the red head across the street

101
00:05:15,530 --> 00:05:18,130
with the muffin basket. That's a robot, right?

102
00:05:18,200 --> 00:05:19,860
Funny and likes to gossip.

103
00:05:19,930 --> 00:05:22,900
We're gonna get along just fine.
Yes, we are.

104
00:05:25,500 --> 00:05:28,330
Wait. Stop.

105
00:05:28,400 --> 00:05:31,430
Could we just rest for a second?

106
00:05:31,500 --> 00:05:34,500
We've only gone four blocks.

107
00:05:34,560 --> 00:05:37,200
Okay, I lied.

108
00:05:37,260 --> 00:05:38,660
I hate running.

109
00:05:38,730 --> 00:05:40,660
Well, why didn't you say something?

110
00:05:40,730 --> 00:05:44,130
We've been doing this for a week.
Because we were starting to become friends,

111
00:05:44,200 --> 00:05:46,730
and you like to run, and I like to...

112
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:48,960
sit and...

113
00:05:49,030 --> 00:05:50,930
One of us had to give.

114
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:53,730
Hi, Susan!
Oh, hi, Helen, Ed.

115
00:05:53,800 --> 00:05:55,260
I would have introduced you,

116
00:05:55,330 --> 00:05:57,400
but once Helen starts talking, she doesn't shut up.

117
00:05:57,460 --> 00:06:01,160
Right. Ed told me that.
Oh, you met Ed?

118
00:06:01,230 --> 00:06:04,500
Oh, yeah. I've gotten to know him quite well.

119
00:06:04,560 --> 00:06:05,760
Yeah?

120
00:06:05,830 --> 00:06:07,760
We're kinda...

121
00:06:07,830 --> 00:06:09,200
doing it.

122
00:06:10,260 --> 00:06:12,330
Doing what?

123
00:06:12,400 --> 00:06:14,960
It.

124
00:06:15,030 --> 00:06:16,830
Ed is married.

125
00:06:16,900 --> 00:06:20,030
Yeah, I'm a naughty girl.

126
00:06:20,100 --> 00:06:23,530
No, you're being immoral.

127
00:06:23,600 --> 00:06:25,700
You're committing adultery.

128
00:06:25,760 --> 00:06:30,360
Actually, Ed's committing adultery. I'm just getting laid.

129
00:06:30,430 --> 00:06:32,630
You know, forget I ever mentioned it.

130
00:06:32,700 --> 00:06:34,660
I can't forget something like this.

131
00:06:34,730 --> 00:06:37,730
Helen is my very good friend.
I thought you just said that she was...

132
00:06:37,800 --> 00:06:40,700
She is annoying, and I hide when she knocks on my door,

133
00:06:40,760 --> 00:06:44,730
but she does not deserve for you to be wrecking her marriage.

134
00:06:44,800 --> 00:06:46,230
Where are you going?

135
00:06:46,300 --> 00:06:47,830
Home.

136
00:06:47,900 --> 00:06:50,500
Oh, so you're not gonna be my friend anymore?

137
00:06:50,560 --> 00:06:53,800
I don't think so.

138
00:06:53,860 --> 00:06:55,300
I thought you didn't like running.

139
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:57,900
Well, it depends on what I'm running away from!

140
00:07:03,130 --> 00:07:05,560
Hi. I'm the whore that lives down the street.

141
00:07:05,630 --> 00:07:07,400
Could I borrow a cup of condoms?

142
00:07:07,460 --> 00:07:09,760
A cup? Are you sure that'll be enough?

143
00:07:09,830 --> 00:07:12,030
Look, I know that you don't like me,

144
00:07:12,100 --> 00:07:15,160
but I am here to do you a favor anyway.

145
00:07:16,660 --> 00:07:18,600
I was out to dinner last night,

146
00:07:18,660 --> 00:07:21,560
and I saw your husband with another woman.
Really?

147
00:07:21,630 --> 00:07:23,760
I feel bad saying it,

148
00:07:23,830 --> 00:07:28,100
but if I were in your shoes, I would want to know.

149
00:07:28,160 --> 00:07:29,700
You're welcome.

150
00:07:29,760 --> 00:07:32,500
Oh, I get it.

151
00:07:32,560 --> 00:07:36,500
So you feel I judged you, and for revenge,

152
00:07:36,560 --> 00:07:38,960
you're trying to make me insecure about my marriage.

153
00:07:39,030 --> 00:07:40,930
If I wanted revenge,

154
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:44,230
I would have joined them and made it a threesome.

155
00:07:44,300 --> 00:07:46,200
You know, Karl would never cheat,

156
00:07:46,260 --> 00:07:49,630
and the woman he was with... Brandi, his secretary,

157
00:07:49,700 --> 00:07:51,900
and he took her out for her birthday.

158
00:07:51,960 --> 00:07:53,860
Oh, the old "I'm taking my secretary

159
00:07:53,930 --> 00:07:55,900
out for her birthday" routine.

160
00:07:55,960 --> 00:07:59,260
Hmm. Nice tip of the hat to the classics.

161
00:07:59,330 --> 00:08:02,600
Okay, well, since you're on this moral roll,

162
00:08:02,660 --> 00:08:04,560
why don't we walk over to Helen's?

163
00:08:04,630 --> 00:08:06,530
And I will introduce you. We can have some tea,

164
00:08:06,600 --> 00:08:08,500
and then you two could swap stories

165
00:08:08,560 --> 00:08:10,430
about Ed's favorite positions.

166
00:08:10,500 --> 00:08:14,330
What I do and what Brandi's doing is completely different.

167
00:08:14,400 --> 00:08:15,430
How?

168
00:08:15,500 --> 00:08:18,830
I'm not looking to break up anyone's marriage.

169
00:08:18,900 --> 00:08:21,030
I'm in it for a little fun, some free meals

170
00:08:21,100 --> 00:08:24,000
and to help an unhappy man through his midlife crisis.

171
00:08:24,060 --> 00:08:28,660
Wow. You're just a giver.

172
00:08:28,730 --> 00:08:30,260
Fine.

173
00:08:30,330 --> 00:08:32,530
Use all of your energy judging me

174
00:08:32,600 --> 00:08:34,500
and ignore the real problem.

175
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:37,360
But let me tell you something.

176
00:08:37,430 --> 00:08:39,330
This is my area of expertise,

177
00:08:39,400 --> 00:08:41,330
and I saw the look in that woman's eyes.

178
00:08:41,400 --> 00:08:45,000
She's not in it for the free meals. She's in it for keeps.

179
00:08:49,430 --> 00:08:51,100
You should leave now.

180
00:08:51,160 --> 00:08:53,030
You know, Susan,

181
00:08:53,100 --> 00:08:55,600
I'm trying to help my neighbor out.

182
00:08:55,660 --> 00:09:00,260
I thought it was the moral thing to do.

183
00:09:04,060 --> 00:09:06,000
Three weeks later, I found Brandi's bra

184
00:09:06,060 --> 00:09:09,860
in Karl's glove compartment, and, well, you know the rest.

185
00:09:09,930 --> 00:09:12,900
Say what you want about Edie, she really understood men.

186
00:09:12,960 --> 00:09:16,600
I should hope so. After all those years of research...

187
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:19,900
I can't help thinking about

188
00:09:19,960 --> 00:09:23,160
all the times Edie and I sniped at each other.

189
00:09:23,230 --> 00:09:25,130
We could have been good friends.

190
00:09:25,200 --> 00:09:28,430
Well, if she knew what you're about to do for her,

191
00:09:28,500 --> 00:09:30,560
she'd forgive you for everything.

192
00:09:38,130 --> 00:09:40,560
okay, my hour's up. Someone else hold Edie now.

193
00:09:40,630 --> 00:09:42,600
Mm. I'll take her.

194
00:09:48,860 --> 00:09:50,760
Kinda looks like cat litter.

195
00:09:50,830 --> 00:09:53,160
Lynette, don't look at Edie.

196
00:09:53,230 --> 00:09:56,630
Or what, I'll turn to stone? She's all rough and gritty.

197
00:09:56,700 --> 00:09:59,560
Uh, Gaby, before we learn what Edie tastes like...

198
00:09:59,630 --> 00:10:01,030
I got it.

199
00:10:01,100 --> 00:10:03,660
I think a little more reverence for the dead is order.

200
00:10:03,730 --> 00:10:05,660
Oh, please. We're talking about Edie.

201
00:10:05,730 --> 00:10:08,330
A little more irreverence is what we need.

202
00:10:08,400 --> 00:10:11,030
Give it.

203
00:10:17,160 --> 00:10:21,530
Do you guys remember when you
took turns driving me to chemo?

204
00:10:21,600 --> 00:10:24,600
Well, none of you did it like Edie.

205
00:10:26,030 --> 00:10:27,460
Hey, Lynette.

206
00:10:27,530 --> 00:10:29,960
Hey.

207
00:10:30,030 --> 00:10:31,100
How you feelin'?

208
00:10:31,160 --> 00:10:32,730
Eh, same.

209
00:10:33,400 --> 00:10:35,430
Well, here's the DVD you asked for.

210
00:10:35,500 --> 00:10:38,630
Thanks. I'll watch it during chemo if I'm  not too tired.

211
00:10:38,700 --> 00:10:41,400
Here we go.

212
00:10:41,460 --> 00:10:43,700
Oh, hi, Edie.

213
00:10:43,760 --> 00:10:45,660
Hi, ugh. What is that?

214
00:10:45,730 --> 00:10:48,000
It's a health shake of fermented brown rice,

215
00:10:48,060 --> 00:10:49,530
and for her entry,

216
00:10:49,600 --> 00:10:52,660
a salad of radish, burdock root and bok choy.

217
00:10:52,730 --> 00:10:55,100
Mmm. What's for dessert, waterboarding?

218
00:10:55,160 --> 00:10:56,900
Thanks.

219
00:10:57,360 --> 00:10:59,200
I can't get comfortable.

220
00:10:59,260 --> 00:11:02,030
Could you fluff my pillows?
Of course.

221
00:11:03,760 --> 00:11:05,700
Well, I've got errands to run,

222
00:11:05,760 --> 00:11:09,200
and I'll be back to drive you to chemo.
Before you go, would you put my socks back on?

223
00:11:09,260 --> 00:11:12,530
My feet are cold again.

224
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:15,260
Oh, of course.

225
00:11:15,330 --> 00:11:18,030
Katherine, you have got stuff to do.

226
00:11:18,100 --> 00:11:20,360
Why don't I take her to chemo?

227
00:11:20,430 --> 00:11:22,030
It's fine.

228
00:11:22,100 --> 00:11:23,530
Okay.

229
00:11:23,600 --> 00:11:25,160
See you tomorrow then.

230
00:11:25,230 --> 00:11:26,600
Bye.

231
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:32,130
Okay, where's your coat?

232
00:11:32,200 --> 00:11:34,860
Why?
Chemo's not until 5:00.

233
00:11:34,930 --> 00:11:39,000
Yeah, I've gotta make a little stop on the way.

234
00:11:44,930 --> 00:11:47,900
Edie!
Whoo!

235
00:11:47,960 --> 00:11:49,400
Been here before?

236
00:11:49,760 --> 00:11:51,960
A couple of times. You're gonna love it. Hey!

237
00:11:52,030 --> 00:11:53,930
Love it? I have cancer.

238
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:56,930
I probably shouldn't even use the ladies' room in this place.

239
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,300
Oh, there isn't a ladies' room, so that's not a problem.

240
00:11:59,360 --> 00:12:01,230
Um, I...

241
00:12:01,300 --> 00:12:04,460
Edie, I have chemo in half an hour.

242
00:12:04,530 --> 00:12:08,360
Fine. Then we better start drinking.
I'm  not supposed to drink.

243
00:12:08,430 --> 00:12:11,330
And they're not supposed to do tattoos in the kitchen,

244
00:12:11,400 --> 00:12:14,300
but I have a bald eagle on my ass that says otherwise.

245
00:12:14,360 --> 00:12:16,300
Two tequila shooters!

246
00:12:16,360 --> 00:12:20,060
Hey, Edie!
Reggie! Oh, I thought you were in Florida.

247
00:12:20,130 --> 00:12:23,060
Nah. That was just a body they identified as me.

248
00:12:23,130 --> 00:12:26,260
Oh. Reggie, this is my friend Lynette.

249
00:12:26,330 --> 00:12:28,660
I'm trying to cheer her up a little.

250
00:12:28,730 --> 00:12:30,900
Right on. You wanna shoot some stick?

251
00:12:30,960 --> 00:12:32,000
Uh...

252
00:12:32,060 --> 00:12:33,500
No, thanks.

253
00:12:33,560 --> 00:12:36,300
Oh, come on. You can totally take him.

254
00:12:36,360 --> 00:12:39,960
No, I can't. Uh, see? Cancer.

255
00:12:40,030 --> 00:12:42,600
Oh. No sweat.

256
00:12:47,200 --> 00:12:49,700
I'll play you one-handed.

257
00:12:51,800 --> 00:12:54,400
Can you excuse us for one second?

258
00:12:57,500 --> 00:13:01,200
I need to go to chemo. I have...
Cancer. Yeah, I heard.

259
00:13:03,130 --> 00:13:05,160
And what do you want from me?

260
00:13:05,230 --> 00:13:07,930
I want you to fluff your own pillows.

261
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:10,300
You need to start fighting this thing.

262
00:13:10,360 --> 00:13:12,200
I'm  doing the best I can.

263
00:13:12,260 --> 00:13:13,700
