00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:46,600
Yeah, Gaby, in hindsight,

530
00:29:46,660 --> 00:29:50,400
maybe you shouldn't have told that part of the story.
Oh, pfft.

531
00:29:50,460 --> 00:29:52,460
I think we're here.

532
00:30:05,300 --> 00:30:09,300
So are we ready for this?

533
00:30:09,360 --> 00:30:11,700
I don't know.

534
00:30:11,760 --> 00:30:15,160
Can you ever be ready to tell a boy that his mother is dead?

535
00:30:25,100 --> 00:30:27,160
Hey, Travers.

536
00:30:29,630 --> 00:30:32,160
Remember us?

537
00:30:33,400 --> 00:30:34,900
Sure.

538
00:30:34,960 --> 00:30:37,160
Wow. You brought the whole neighborhood with you.

539
00:30:39,300 --> 00:30:41,660
Did my mom come with you?

540
00:30:46,260 --> 00:30:48,160
We brought you some muffins.

541
00:30:48,230 --> 00:30:50,200
You can share them with your roommates

542
00:30:50,260 --> 00:30:52,260
or maybe a favorite teacher.

543
00:30:55,000 --> 00:30:56,860
What's going on?

544
00:30:56,930 --> 00:30:59,530
Is my mom in trouble or something?

545
00:31:03,400 --> 00:31:05,360
Come here.

546
00:31:08,930 --> 00:31:12,430
I'm afraid we have some bad news.

547
00:31:12,500 --> 00:31:15,860
Your mom was in a very serious accident,

548
00:31:15,930 --> 00:31:20,000
and I am so sorry...

549
00:31:20,060 --> 00:31:21,960
but she passed away.

550
00:31:25,730 --> 00:31:27,230
She died?

551
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:34,130
When?

552
00:31:34,200 --> 00:31:35,860
A couple of days ago.

553
00:31:35,930 --> 00:31:39,430
We've been trying to get in touch with your dad,

554
00:31:39,500 --> 00:31:40,960
but he's still out of the country.

555
00:31:41,030 --> 00:31:43,060
And your mom's new husband's never met you,

556
00:31:43,130 --> 00:31:46,060
so he thought it would be best if we told you.

557
00:31:49,230 --> 00:31:50,630
Wow.

558
00:31:52,300 --> 00:31:54,230
If you'd like, we could give you a moment.

559
00:31:54,300 --> 00:31:56,630
No.

560
00:31:58,260 --> 00:31:59,630
I'm okay.

561
00:32:01,400 --> 00:32:04,500
Well, I have a class.

562
00:32:07,600 --> 00:32:09,730
Uh, I'm sure the school will understand

563
00:32:09,800 --> 00:32:11,700
if you need to miss a few days.

564
00:32:11,760 --> 00:32:13,530
I don't need to do that.

565
00:32:13,600 --> 00:32:16,660
I mean, I'm sorry she's dead, but we weren't very close.

566
00:32:16,730 --> 00:32:19,060
Still, she was your mother.

567
00:32:19,130 --> 00:32:21,030
Technically.

568
00:32:21,100 --> 00:32:23,060
But not a very good one.

569
00:32:23,130 --> 00:32:25,600
Look, Travers, we're all moms here.

570
00:32:25,660 --> 00:32:27,600
We've all made mistakes with our kids,

571
00:32:27,660 --> 00:32:29,860
and what we count on is when they grow up,

572
00:32:29,930 --> 00:32:33,560
they'll forgive us.
My mom didn't even try to raise me.

573
00:32:33,630 --> 00:32:37,330
I mean, she just handed me to my father and walked away.

574
00:32:37,400 --> 00:32:40,060
How do you expect me to forgive that?

575
00:32:40,130 --> 00:32:41,760
Look, I'm sorry.

576
00:32:41,830 --> 00:32:45,660
I don't mean to be rude, but I'm gonna be late.

577
00:32:45,730 --> 00:32:47,360
Hey! Hey, hey, hey, hey. Wait a second.

578
00:32:47,430 --> 00:32:50,560
Travers, you need to know something about your mom,

579
00:32:50,630 --> 00:32:53,730
and I'm gonna tell you. Now sit down.

580
00:32:53,800 --> 00:32:56,230
And I'd only known your mom about a year

581
00:32:56,300 --> 00:32:59,230
when she came over to my house this one day.

582
00:33:00,900 --> 00:33:04,630
Hey, Karen! Your porch light's on.

583
00:33:07,830 --> 00:33:10,730
Whoa. Sitting in your bathrobe drinking,

584
00:33:10,730 --> 00:33:11,800
and you didn't call me?

585
00:33:13,360 --> 00:33:15,400
I kinda wanted to be alone.

586
00:33:17,460 --> 00:33:19,260
Why?

587
00:33:21,130 --> 00:33:23,600
It's the anniversary of my son's death.

588
00:33:23,660 --> 00:33:25,760
Ohh.

589
00:33:27,960 --> 00:33:29,530
I'm sorry.

590
00:33:29,660 --> 00:33:32,300
Every year I think it'll get easier,

591
00:33:32,360 --> 00:33:34,160
and it never does.

592
00:33:37,530 --> 00:33:39,660
Nothing worse than losing a child.

593
00:33:41,260 --> 00:33:44,600
In a way, you're kinda lucky you don't have any.

594
00:33:44,660 --> 00:33:47,060
Actually, I do.

595
00:33:47,130 --> 00:33:48,960
What?

596
00:33:49,030 --> 00:33:51,200
Mm, I have a son.

597
00:33:52,360 --> 00:33:55,860
You lived here a year. How do I not know this?

598
00:33:55,930 --> 00:33:57,900
Because he lives with his father.

599
00:33:57,960 --> 00:34:02,000
When I got divorced, I gave him full custody,

600
00:34:02,560 --> 00:34:04,630
so I kinda know how you feel.

601
00:34:07,800 --> 00:34:10,660
I mean, we've both lost kids.

602
00:34:10,660 --> 00:34:12,290
No.

603
00:34:13,230 --> 00:34:14,860
I lost a kid.

604
00:34:14,930 --> 00:34:16,800
You gave yours away.

605
00:34:16,860 --> 00:34:20,060
And you have the nerve to tell me you know how I feel?

606
00:34:20,130 --> 00:34:22,500
I gave him up because I wanted to protect him.

607
00:34:22,560 --> 00:34:24,330
From who?

608
00:34:24,400 --> 00:34:25,860
From me.

609
00:34:25,930 --> 00:34:29,230
You know, I tried to be a good mom. I really did.

610
00:34:29,300 --> 00:34:31,860
But I know myself.

611
00:34:31,930 --> 00:34:33,660
And if he...

612
00:34:33,730 --> 00:34:35,700
if he was gonna grow up normal,

613
00:34:35,760 --> 00:34:37,800
he needed to get away from me.

614
00:34:37,860 --> 00:34:39,400
What a cop-out.

615
00:34:39,460 --> 00:34:41,630
I think you're just being selfish.

616
00:34:41,700 --> 00:34:43,600
You know, trust me, Karen,

617
00:34:43,660 --> 00:34:45,600
There is nothing that you could say

618
00:34:45,660 --> 00:34:47,760
to make me think less about myself than I already do.

619
00:34:47,830 --> 00:34:51,630
But if it gives him a chance, it's worth it.

620
00:34:51,700 --> 00:34:54,900
Aren't you afraid he's gonna hate you?

621
00:34:57,260 --> 00:35:01,000
I love him enough to let him hate me.

622
00:35:13,060 --> 00:35:16,160
Well, I hope you're not making a big mistake.

623
00:35:23,830 --> 00:35:25,500
Well...

624
00:35:27,560 --> 00:35:29,260
Me too.

625
00:35:33,230 --> 00:35:36,960
So I'm not defending everything she did, Travers,

626
00:35:37,030 --> 00:35:40,360
but you have to know, she loved you,

627
00:35:40,430 --> 00:35:43,600
more than you can imagine.

628
00:35:47,760 --> 00:35:50,300
I really need to get to class.

629
00:35:57,930 --> 00:36:00,830
Bup, bup, bup. I believe I called shotgun.

630
00:36:00,900 --> 00:36:02,800
God, she is so good at that.

631
00:36:02,860 --> 00:36:04,760
She should be. She's been doing it

632
00:36:04,830 --> 00:36:08,230
since she rode shotgun on an actual stagecoach.
Hey. Hey.

633
00:36:11,860 --> 00:36:14,460
I realized... I never thanked you

634
00:36:14,460 --> 00:36:16,800
for coming all the way out here just to tell me.

635
00:36:17,860 --> 00:36:20,330
That was really cool of you.

636
00:36:20,330 --> 00:36:22,460
We felt we owed it to your mom.

637
00:36:23,330 --> 00:36:25,030
Oh, my god. I can't believe we forgot.

638
00:36:24,300 --> 00:36:25,860
What?

639
00:36:30,400 --> 00:36:32,130
We, uh...

640
00:36:32,200 --> 00:36:35,460
also came to give you your mom's ashes.

641
00:36:40,160 --> 00:36:43,260
We thought you might wanna scatter them somewhere.

642
00:36:46,900 --> 00:36:49,530
Unless that's a little...

643
00:36:49,600 --> 00:36:52,260
weird for you.

644
00:36:54,200 --> 00:36:56,230
Why don't you guys take 'em?

645
00:36:57,860 --> 00:37:00,930
Are you sure?

646
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:03,660
Yeah.

647
00:37:03,730 --> 00:37:06,500
You were her best friends.

648
00:37:08,200 --> 00:37:11,300
I'm sure you could think of the perfect place to put her.

649
00:37:21,900 --> 00:37:24,500
Okay, we're here.

650
00:37:24,560 --> 00:37:26,630
Guys... Wake up.

651
00:37:26,700 --> 00:37:29,700
Guys?

652
00:37:32,400 --> 00:37:35,060
We're home. Get out.

653
00:37:35,130 --> 00:37:37,730
Lord, Lynette. You nearly gave me a heart attack.

654
00:37:37,800 --> 00:37:40,660
Yeah, I'd like to see Edie again, but not tonight.

655
00:37:40,730 --> 00:37:42,630
Oh, I think my leg's asleep.

656
00:37:42,700 --> 00:37:45,160
Actually, that's my leg. Get your hand off.

657
00:37:46,700 --> 00:37:48,900
Lynette, thank you again for driving.

658
00:37:48,960 --> 00:37:51,000
You bet.
Hold it.

659
00:37:51,060 --> 00:37:54,460
We still gotta figure out where we're gonna spread the ashes.

660
00:37:55,900 --> 00:37:59,160
Now it's gotta be someplace that was meaningful to Edie.

661
00:37:59,230 --> 00:38:03,260
Well, Edie once told me she lost
her virginity in a cow pasture.

662
00:38:03,330 --> 00:38:05,230
If we can find that exact field...

663
00:38:05,300 --> 00:38:07,560
We'd find a lot of traumatized cows.

664
00:38:09,760 --> 00:38:12,160
Do we really need to do this tonight? They're ashes.

665
00:38:12,230 --> 00:38:14,560
It's not like they're gonna go bad.

666
00:38:14,630 --> 00:38:16,230
Fine. We'll talk tomorrow.

667
00:38:31,460 --> 00:38:35,000
Oh, Edie, what are we gonna do with you?

668
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:13,600
Subtle as always, I see.

669
00:39:26,200 --> 00:39:28,460
This was a wonderful idea, Karen.

670
00:39:28,530 --> 00:39:31,660
It wasn't exactly mine. Now be careful. You're spilling Edie.

671
00:39:31,730 --> 00:39:34,560
Urn is empty.

672
00:39:34,630 --> 00:39:36,030
Let's do it.

673
00:39:36,100 --> 00:39:38,360
Shouldn't we say something first?

674
00:39:38,430 --> 00:39:40,260
Like what?

675
00:39:40,330 --> 00:39:42,200
I don't know.

676
00:39:42,260 --> 00:39:45,060
A few words describing how we felt about her?

677
00:39:45,130 --> 00:39:47,660
I don't think Edie would want us to get all sappy.

678
00:39:47,730 --> 00:39:50,630
Well, I think if we're quick about it, she'd be fine.

679
00:39:50,700 --> 00:39:52,130
Here's a thought...

680
00:39:52,200 --> 00:39:55,360
We all say one word that sums up what we thought of her.

681
00:39:55,430 --> 00:39:59,230
And then we dump her?
Then we dump her.

682
00:39:59,300 --> 00:40:02,100
Just one word. This is hard.

683
00:40:02,160 --> 00:40:03,200
Mm.

684
00:40:03,260 --> 00:40:05,530
Okay, I got one. I'll go first.

685
00:40:05,600 --> 00:40:09,260
Edie Britt was sexy.

686
00:40:11,330 --> 00:40:13,130
Perceptive.

687
00:40:13,200 --> 00:40:15,900
Strong.

688
00:40:15,960 --> 00:40:18,460
Beautiful.
Mm-hmm.

689
00:40:20,660 --> 00:40:22,060
I need four words.

690
00:40:22,130 --> 00:40:23,860
Ay.

691
00:40:23,930 --> 00:40:26,830
Okay. I want to do Edie justice, and for that to happen,

692
00:40:26,900 --> 00:40:30,960
I need four words, okay?
Edie would so not be surprised you're ruining this moment.

693
00:40:31,030 --> 00:40:34,360
Go ahead, Susan. What are your four words for Edie?

694
00:40:34,430 --> 00:40:38,160
One of a kind.

695
00:40:43,100 --> 00:40:45,760
Now it's time.

696
00:40:48,460 --> 00:40:49,900
And that is

697
00:40:49,960 --> 00:40:53,500
how wisteria lane came to be my final resting place.

698
00:40:56,530 --> 00:41:00,400
My ashes were spread over grass I had once walked on...

699
00:41:03,560 --> 00:41:07,200
Beneath trees that had once given me shade...

700
00:41:09,630 --> 00:41:14,000
On top of roses I once admired...

701
00:41:16,030 --> 00:41:20,900
And beside fences I once gossiped over.

702
00:41:20,960 --> 00:41:24,330
And after my friends had finished saying good-bye,

703
00:41:24,400 --> 00:41:29,630
a wind came along and took what was left of me into the air.

704
00:41:31,330 --> 00:41:33,960
As I looked down on the world,

705
00:41:34,030 --> 00:41:36,760
I began to let go of it.

706
00:41:36,830 --> 00:41:39,430
I let go of white picket fences

707
00:41:39,500 --> 00:41:42,030
and cars in driveways,

708
00:41:42,100 --> 00:41:45,800
coffee cups and vacuum caners.

709
00:41:45,860 --> 00:41:49,630
I let go of all those things which seem so ordinary,

710
00:41:49,700 --> 00:41:53,160
but when you put them together, they make up a life...

711
00:41:53,230 --> 00:41:58,460
a life that really was one of a kind.

712
00:41:58,530 --> 00:41:59,960
I'll tell you something...

713
00:42:00,030 --> 00:42:04,160
It's not hard to die when you know you have lived,

714
00:42:04,230 --> 00:42:06,000
and I did.

715
00:42:06,060 --> 00:42:08,930
Oh, how I lived.

